lomerular endothelial cells lomerular endothelial cells are highly specialised cells with regions of attenuated cytoplasm punctuated by numerous fenestrae, circular transcellular pores 60β€“80 nm in diameter [31, 32]. nitially these fenestrations were thought of as empty and to therefore provide little barrier to the passage of proteins. tandard fixation protocols for electron microscopy do not preserve the glycocalyx, but newer fixation techniques have allowed the demonstration of a glomerular endothelial glycocalyx of 200β€“400 nm in thickness [33, 34]. his glycocalyx covers both fenestral and inter-fenestral domains of the glomerular endothelial cell luminal surface.tudies of the systemic endothelial glycocalyx are instructive here. he glycocalyx is a dynamic, hydrated layer largely composed of glycoproteins and proteoglycans with adsorbed plasma proteins. eparan sulphate proteoglycans (s) are largely responsible for the negative charge characteristics of the glycocalyx. emoval of the glycocalyx increases vascular protein permeability, providing evidence that it hinders the passage of macromolecules [35, 36]. ompared with those without, capillaries with fenestrations are much more permeable to water and small solutes, but not to proteins. hese characteristics can only be explained by the glycocalyx [37].herefore, the presence of a significant glomerular endothelial glycocalyx implies that the glomerular endothelium significantly contributes to the barrier to macromolecules [31, 32, 38]. xperimental data support this view: in mice treated with glycocalyx-degrading enzymes the distance between luminal lipid droplets and the glomerular endothelium was decreased, and this was accompanied by an increase in  [39]. n rats, under normal perfusion conditions albumin is confined to the glomerular capillary lumen and endothelial fenestrae [40]. ndothelial glycocalyx has the correct anatomical distribution (on the surface of endothelial cells, including in fenestral openings) to explain this distribution. eactive oxygen species (), which are known to disrupt the glycocalyx [41], cause torrential proteinuria without any identifiable structural changes in the  using standard electron microscopy techniques [42]. urthermore, the ability of human glomerular endothelial cell glycocalyx to form a permeability barrier to macromolecules can be directly demonstrated in vitro [43].

