Passage of albumin across the normal 
iltration ater filters across the  via gaps through or between cells rather than through the cell cytoplasm. herefore, the high hydraulic conductivity of the  depends on the presence of fenestrae and filtration slits. ifty per cent of the hydraulic resistance of the  is afforded by the two cell layers (endothelium and podocyte foot processes), and 50% by the  [46].
olute flux olute flux (including albumin) from the glomerular capillary occurs by a combination of convection (i.e. being swept along by the filtration of water) and diffusion [31]. he rate of convection of a solute depends on the filtration rate and on its reflection coefficient. eflection coefficients are related to solute size, larger solutes having higher reflection coefficients.  value of 1 indicates that a molecule is totally excluded. he rate of diffusion of a solute depends on the concentration gradient and its diffusivity (solute permeability). he diffusivity of a solute decreases with increasing size.  measure of overall flux of a solute is given by the sieving coefficient: the filtrate to plasma concentration ratio. he sieving coefficient for albumin across the normal  is <0.001 [47]. he ratio of the contribution of convective to diffusive flux (the eclet number) increases with increasing molecular size. hat is, for small molecules, diffusion dominates; for larger molecules, convection dominates. he eclet number for albumin across the normal  is near to unity, so both diffusion and convection contribute [48]. ence, an increase in  will result in an increase in the convective flux of albumin. owever, despite this, the best estimates indicate that even a 50% increase in filtration rate would only increase urinary albumin in the sub-microalbuminuric range, as the majority of the excess albumin is reabsorbed by the tubules [47]. herefore, for albumin flux to increase sufficiently to produce microalbuminuria (assuming normal tubular reuptake), the  must be physically altered in such a way as to increase the sieving coefficient of albumin across it.odels have been developed to correlate the macromolecular sieving properties of the  with the structure and properties of its components [31]. hese indicate that the  functions as a whole, with each layer having an important contribution to selective permeability. hereas hydraulic resistances are essentially additive, sieving coefficients are multiplicative. his relationship means that a change in one element significantly affects the overall protein permeability to the same degree, i.e. a 10% change in permeability of any one layer will produce a 10% change in overall  permeability. mportantly, this means that, regardless of which layer is most restrictive, a change in the permeability of any layer of the  could potentially account for microalbuminuria.Passage of albumin across the normal GFB
Filtration Water filters across the GFB via gaps through or between cells rather than through the cell cytoplasm. Therefore, the high hydraulic conductivity of the GFB depends on the presence of fenestrae and filtration slits. Fifty per cent of the hydraulic resistance of the GFB is afforded by the two cell layers (endothelium and podocyte foot processes), and 50% by the GBM [46].
Solute flux Solute flux (including albumin) from the glomerular capillary occurs by a combination of convection (i.e. being swept along by the filtration of water) and diffusion [31]. The rate of convection of a solute depends on the filtration rate and on its reflection coefficient. Reflection coefficients are related to solute size, larger solutes having higher reflection coefficients. A value of 1 indicates that a molecule is totally excluded. The rate of diffusion of a solute depends on the concentration gradient and its diffusivity (solute permeability). The diffusivity of a solute decreases with increasing size. A measure of overall flux of a solute is given by the sieving coefficient: the filtrate to plasma concentration ratio. The sieving coefficient for albumin across the normal GFB is <0.001 [47]. The ratio of the contribution of convective to diffusive flux (the Peclet number) increases with increasing molecular size. That is, for small molecules, diffusion dominates; for larger molecules, convection dominates. The Peclet number for albumin across the normal GFB is near to unity, so both diffusion and convection contribute [48]. Hence, an increase in GFR will result in an increase in the convective flux of albumin. However, despite this, the best estimates indicate that even a 50% increase in filtration rate would only increase urinary albumin in the sub-microalbuminuric range, as the majority of the excess albumin is reabsorbed by the tubules [47]. Therefore, for albumin flux to increase sufficiently to produce microalbuminuria (assuming normal tubular reuptake), the GFB must be physically altered in such a way as to increase the sieving coefficient of albumin across it.Models have been developed to correlate the macromolecular sieving properties of the GFB with the structure and properties of its components [31]. These indicate that the GFB functions as a whole, with each layer having an important contribution to selective permeability. Whereas hydraulic resistances are essentially additive, sieving coefficients are multiplicative. This relationship means that a change in one element significantly affects the overall protein permeability to the same degree, i.e. a 10% change in permeability of any one layer will produce a 10% change in overall GFB permeability. Importantly, this means that, regardless of which layer is most restrictive, a change in the permeability of any layer of the GFB could potentially account for microalbuminuria.
